    <item>
      <title>14.16 Girls&amp;#8217; Night Out</title>
      <link>https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-16-girls-night-out/</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-16-girls-night-out/</guid>
      <pubDate>Thu, 02 Jan 2025 14:24:04 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;main class="wp-block-group is-layout-flow wp-block-group-is-layout-flow"&gt; &lt;div class="wp-block-group is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained"&gt;&lt;h1 class="wp-block-post-title"&gt;14.16 Girls&amp;#8217; Night&amp;nbsp;Out&lt;/h1&gt;   &lt;div style="height:1px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;   &lt;/div&gt;   &lt;div class="entry-content wp-block-post-content is-layout-constrained wp-block-post-content-is-layout-constrained"&gt; &lt;p&gt;(&lt;a href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-15-letters/"&gt;Previous Chapter&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Just as Kokuyou wrote in his letter, Yo returned to the capital.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;She certainly looks beat.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The sight of Yo, having clearly lost weight in the span of a single month, made Maomao realise it fully. If anything, she felt it was commendable for the girl yet in her mid-teens to have endured a full month of it too.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I could still work,” Yo said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Still work—that was true. But if she kept at it…&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“You might be able to keep going, but you’ll be burning yourself out,” En’en said. “The human body can recover to some degree, but it has its limits. Rather than overworking yourself without rest to the point of a breakdown, you are planning to return after a short break, right? Then, it is important you recover your energy.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“B-but.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“The job you’re doing is something we can’t do.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;She’s saying something sensible!&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao was shocked for a moment, but En’en was originally someone with common sense. When it didn’t involve Yao, she did say decent things.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;En’en’s obsession with Yao was a bit abnormal, even if she had a debt of gratitude to the other woman. It would be better if she was a little more contained.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“She’s right. Consider that your health comes first.” Changsha also agreed with En’en’s opinion.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“At least, I don’t think Court Physician Liu is ever a hard taskmaster for the court physicians. Same goes for the court ladies. He immediately kicks you out if you’re useless, but seeing as Yo has been given some time off, I can see that you have been useful. You should be proud of that fact,” Yao added.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yes, yes. The most important thing for Yo-san right now is energy. Your weight isn’t enough either. And so, let’s eat up today!” Chue said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Why is Chue-san here?” Maomao spoke out in doubt.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao and the others were currently at a restaurant near the dorms. They also had a private room set up, so they—being an entirely female group—could eat without strange customers bothering them.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Changsha took Yo’s return as an opportunity to propose a get-together. As luck would have it, everyone was on the early shift, so they all hurried over to the restaurant, but a bonus person came along.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Myy, don’t mind Chue-san. Everyone knows Chue-san, and it’s quite costly to rent a room, right? It’ll be cheaper if we split it between more people, riiight?” Chue said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I get your logic, but isn’t Chue-san the one who eats the most among us?” Maomao asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Huhuhu, huhuhu, isn’t that fine, Maomao-san? This very Chue-san was the one who found the shop that matched everyone’s demands in no time, you know.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Well, I guess you’re right.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It had private rooms, had mild flavours yet was delicious, &lt;em&gt;and &lt;/em&gt;was close to the dorms. Maomao had never been to this shop either because of its low-key entrance. She was impressed that such a nice place existed.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Changsha was going around the table, pouring tea. Maomao wanted to drink wine, but they wanted to refrain from drinking in consideration of Yao’s constitution—Yo was still low in energy as well. She had a feeling that Changsha would be good at drinking, but it didn’t seem like the other woman would be up for ordering wine while she was pouring tea. And so, Maomao had no choice but to read the room and conform with everyone else.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Now, now, everyone. Eat up and enjoooy.” Chue snatched the dishes away from the staff who entered the room. There were bamboo steamers containing dumplings with translucent skin and a soup with fluffy egg. Light, salty flavours. The seasoning had been adjusted to taste, so you could say the dishes were perfect for Yao.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yo, I don’t think you’re in the mood for it, but you should eat first to recover your strength. Honestly, you won’t be able to return to the site if you don’t eat anything here and don’t recover. Otherwise, would you prefer to never go back to such a place ever again and stay skinny forever?”  Changsha’s tone was quite casual compared to how she spoke with Maomao and the others. It was partly because they were colleagues and she was much closer to Yo than the others.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Yo looked upset at first, but then she gave a big sigh and reached for the bamboo steamer.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Alrightyyyy, one moment. Chue-san will serve everyone their portions.” Chue was spinning small plates on her fingers. With how overly-dexterous she was, no one would believe that her right hand was disabled. Since her left hand was moving more than twice as usual, she could move her non-paralysed right elbow and above to support her left side.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“You don’t need to do that.” Yao reached out with her own chopsticks. En’en was restless, wanting to serve Yao her portion.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“No, no. It’s not a problem for Yao-san and the others to take as you please, but please don’t forget that your juniors have a tacit understanding to only eat the dishes their seniors have touched. It will be free for all, free of worries, but there is no alcohol here. And so, Chue-san will serve out small portions of everything, and people who want to eat the leftover portion, that&amp;#8217;s free for the taking.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“There are a few things I won’t eat though,” Yao said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Please pass those to Chue-san. They’ll be eaten up with no leftovers,” Chue said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Wouldn’t the leftover portion be not free for the taking then?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Among the rich and powerful, there was a custom to let servants eat leftovers.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Anyway, all the dishes brought in have been served, so everyone started to eat.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Since this was a dinner meet that included interaction and information sharing, everyone spoke as they ate.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yo-san, sorry about this since we just told you to focus on recovery, but can you give us the news on the locked-down village?” Maomao asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It was a topic that would make people lose their appetites, but Yo was open to her question. “Sure. The situation is not good. However, I can say that it is much better compared to what I saw in the past.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The village where Yo lived in the past only had a few survivors, Yo’s family included.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What’s the extent of infected people?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Around sixty percent of a population of around three hundred people in the village has been fully quarantined. There are deaths, but the speed of the infection is high, likely because people who think themselves completely cured are helping out little by little.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Yo spoke calmly, but everyone around her had pale faces. Only Chue was shovelling food into her mouth. Maomao also tossed a dumpling into her mouth.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Could it be the high-ranking court physicians are planning to wait for it to run its course in the village?” Yao asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yes, but… we’ve already had a few escape attempts, and one person did succeed,” Yo said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Is that okay?” Changsha’s face was pale, but she barely managed to reach for the green vegetable stir-fry.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“He was caught soon after. The escapee and the people he was in contact with got quarantined for a time as well, so it looks like it’s fine.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“That’s a relief.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao thought so too, but there was one thing that caught her attention. “From what I’m hearing, it’s easy to quarantine in this village, right? To say it differently, it’s relatively far from other villages and towns, so it’s a place that doesn’t have much outside contact, right?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Exactly as you say,” Yo said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Then, where did the infection come from?” Maomao’s question wasn’t to blame anyone. She just wanted to confirm where the disease came from.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I don’t know. Actually, it was detected late since they thought it was chickenpox in the beginning as it was only the little kids that caught it long before the adults started getting it too.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Did pedlars visit this village?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“There were a few groups of visitors but none of them appeared to have the poxes. Although, there was a child who accompanied their parent to a nearby town, so people wonder if that was when they got it.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao couldn&amp;#8217;t accept Yo’s answer. “It’s strange, isn’t it?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“It’s strange, indeed.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What’s so strange about it?” Chue asked as she added a generous amount of vinegar into her congee.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Assume that the child got infected in town. Then, to speak of whether that town has a smallpox epidemic…”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“It does not,” Yo said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Yao also found it strange like Maomao did, along with everyone else. “Then, where did the smallpox come from?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It begged the question.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao wasn’t familiar with the kind of outbreak the disease had either. Although she suspected that it came about from a weakened toxin that entered the body. “Did you talk to the child that caught the pox in the beginning?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“&amp;#8230;He seems to have died,” Yo said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao rested her brow on her left hand. She scooped up the egg from the soup with her free right hand. Perhaps due to its mild flavour, she could barely taste it. “It’s scary if the source of the infection is from the neighbouring town.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yes, if it spreads widely there, our efforts to quarantine the village would be all in vain.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Wait. Assuming that there were infected people in that town, and it’s not spreading anymore, so whether they are dead or cured, doesn’t that mean that there is no longer a concern for infection?” Yao’s assessment was reasonable, but there was one thing she left out.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“The bodies of smallpox patients are also infectious, you know,” Maomao said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yes, I’ve been told that it’s better to be careful for around a year. Cremation is advised over burial. Likewise with clothes–they’re dangerous if they have traces of blood or tissue, so you have to sterilise them,” Yo said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Is this true?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It was. Yao wasn’t that knowledgeable in smallpox. Being a court lady that was assistant to court physicians, she had to learn a lot of other things, so her minimal knowledge was reasonable. Let alone Yao, even En’en and Changsha looked like they were learning this for the first time.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“In other words, it means that if the person who infected the child with smallpox had died undiscovered in town, it’ll become a rather terrible matter, right?” Chue said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I guess you can also consider it that way.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;If they consider the worst case scenario, that would be it, but everything had an order of precedence. At present, they probably couldn’t hunt for a dead body that may or may not exist.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;More importantly, they have to consider other ways to resolve it.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Did Kokuyou say what he was going to do?” Maomao asked. She recalled the overly-easy-going man.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yes, Doctor was thinking of ways to protect against it,” Yo said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“It sounded like he was looking for cows.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yes. I believe he is studying cowpox.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao’s eyes widened. “Cowpox?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“It seems like Doctor is thinking that cowpox can be used as the base to protect against it.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“W-wait a moment! I don’t think Kokuyou ever mentioned anything like this before. He said his master’s research hadn’t been left behind or something—” Maomao interrupted and drew closer to Yo.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;She got so close that Chue stepped in between to stop her. “Eaaasy there.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What is the meaning of this?” Maomao asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I believe Doctor isn’t confident about it either. He seems to think that people infected with cowpox would get milder symptoms than human smallpox, so they can be resistant to the disease.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Then we should go find cows as soon as possible,” Maomao declared.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Please wait, Maomao,” En’en said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Let’s wait, Maomao-san,” Chue said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The both of them grabbed onto Maomao’s hand as she was about to fly out.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“There are cases where you can catch smallpox even if you’ve caught cowpox,” Yo said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“&amp;#8230;Then wouldn’t that be pointless?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yes. There are cases where you can prevent smallpox and cases where you don’t.” Yo held up her index fingers. “Doctor’s twin brother caught cowpox, so he could no longer catch human pox. However, his master caught human smallpox even after catching cowpox. He was suffering so much that he got put out of his misery.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Put out of his misery—in other words, he was killed.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Ahhh, is that how it is?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It was consistent with the story of Kokuyou’s past. And it was precisely because of his lack of confidence that he had yet to tell Maomao how to treat it.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;If it were up to Maomao, she would probably try out cowpox for the time being. She had no idea if she would get into contact with human smallpox even if she tested it out.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;I would’ve tested it out if dad never brought it up.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao bit her lip. She couldn’t test it out since Luomen had imposed a sense of responsibility on her. Let’s just say that his ability to anticipate her actions was as expected of him.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Now then, the mood has gotten a bit weird, but the main star of tonight is heeere.” Chue invited in the staff carrying roast duck with a flourish.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The plump duck looked really delicious, but Maomao heard something that bothered her. “Chue-san, this duck couldn’t have been brought in by Chue-san, right?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Unfortunately not. It would have been better if they allowed it,” Chue said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao was relieved to know that it wasn’t Basen’s beloved duck at least.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p class="has-text-align-right"&gt;(Next Chapter)&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div id="jp-post-flair" class="sharedaddy sd-like-enabled"&gt;&lt;div class="sharedaddy sd-sharing-enabled"&gt;&lt;div class="robots-nocontent sd-block sd-social sd-social-official sd-sharing"&gt;&lt;h3 class="sd-title"&gt;Share this:&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="sd-content"&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li class="share-facebook"&gt;&lt;div class="fb-share-button" data-href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-16-girls-night-out/" data-layout="button_count"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li class="share-end"&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class='sharedaddy sd-block sd-like jetpack-likes-widget-wrapper jetpack-likes-widget-unloaded' id='like-post-wrapper-130534757-5218-6778a022bba63' data-src='//widgets.wp.com/likes/index.html?ver=20250104#blog_id=130534757&amp;amp;post_id=5218&amp;amp;origin=shikarito.wordpress.com&amp;amp;obj_id=130534757-5218-6778a022bba63' data-name='like-post-frame-130534757-5218-6778a022bba63' data-title='Like or Reblog'&gt;&lt;div class='likes-widget-placeholder post-likes-widget-placeholder' style='height: 55px;'&gt;&lt;span class='button'&gt;&lt;span&gt;Like&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class='loading'&gt;Loading&amp;#8230;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;span class='sd-text-color'&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;a class='sd-link-color' href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/14-16-girls-night-out/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/main&gt;</description>
